In article <24420v$40i@transfer.stratus.com> cme@ellisun.sw.stratus.com (Carl Ellison) writes:

>If you want to take a provably long-period PRNG and feed it through a
>strong encryption algorithm, the source PRNG itself doesn't need to be
>strong.  You could use a simple counter, starting at some initial value
>(considered part of the key).  The strength of the encryption algorithm
>should be enough to totally hide the starting value of the counter, no
>matter how many sequential values you use (unless it loops).

The length of the period of the PRNG is not the problem; even many very bad
ones have periods longer that all the messages which have been sent.  The
problem is the predictability.


